We recommended to the management to:
Consider augmenting the existing manning complement of both the General Services and Accounting Offices;
Instruct the GSO to retrieve the SSMIs of the procured inventories from prior periods and for those inventories with unavailable SSMIs, reconstruct the documents if the concerned signatories are still available. Also, issue Inventory Custodian Slips to concerned personnel for supplies with serviceable life of more than one year and to prepare the necessary transfer documents for items turned over to other government entity;
Direct the Accounting Office to strategize the periodical issuance to the GSO with the list of inventory items which remained undispensed in the books of accounts and ensure that all SSMIs received from the GSO are timely and properly recognized as appropriate expenditure accounts; and
Ensure the completion of the conduct of physical count of inventory items and enjoin the Accounting and the General Services Offices to coordinate with each other for the periodic reconciliation of their respective inventory records for the preparation of JEVs to establish correct balances.

We recommended to management to:
Instruct the City Treasurer to submit the duly certified list of names of taxpayers and amounts due and collectible for calendar year 2024 to the City Accountant for proper recognition in the books;
Direct the City Accountant to conduct regular and periodic verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of the receivables and identify the dormant accounts for the execution of the procedures on the request for their write-off as provided in the aforementioned circulars;
Make representation with the COA Accounting Systems Development and Other Services Office (ASDOSO) to  facilitate resolution on identified system issues and technical problems;
Direct the City Accountant to obtain all relevant documents for the preparation of the necessary adjusting and correcting entries of the Receivables accounts to reflect the correct balances in the financial reports; and
Consider augmenting the manning complement of the City Accounting Office to fast track review of records, demand for settlement from debtors, and processing of requests for write-off  on dormant and long outstanding accounts.

We recommended to the management to:
Re-organize the Inventory Committee to include only those who can be relieved temporarily of all regular duties for completion of the physical inventory in three months or less;
Enjoin the Inventory Committee to prepare and submit the duly approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory activities for substantial implementation of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts as provided in COA Circular No. 2020-006 to come up with established PPE balances of the city;
Enjoin all department heads through the Inventory Committee to coordinate with the Accounting and General Services Offices to facilitate the conduct of the physical count and reconciliation to establish existence, ownership and condition of the PPE items in their respective departments or offices; and
Direct the City Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries to recognize the purchased motor vehicles and derecognize the donated PPE items from the books of the city through prescribed procedures, as well as the results of the one-time cleansing procedures.

We recommended to the management to:
Direct the implementing/requesting units to coordinate with the City Accounting Office (CAO) and Source Agencies on the retrieval of the MOAs and revisit them for information and proper action on the proper disposition of the unused funds in adherence to the provisions of COA Circular No. 94-013;
Ensure receipts of future financial assistance to be duly covered with Memorandum of Agreements (MOA) with the terms and conditions embodied thereat are faithfully complied with;
Remit what is due to other government agencies to avoid the accumulation of long outstanding balances; and
Direct the CAO to draw the necessary adjusting entries to address the noted discrepancies in the accounts and submit the JEVs to the COA office and facilitate the timely liquidation for all subsequent transfers.

