Evaluation and setting of policies and staffing pattern of the college. 




4.1 The management should evaluate and specify the staffing and service requirements of the school;



4.2 The Board of Trustees should install an adequate and clear policies on: 

Teaching units de-loading;


4.2.2 Creation of another post/assignment/office and allocating corresponding teaching units deductions thereof; if sanctioned by law;



4.2.3 Job specification for newly created position/office/assignment;



4.2.4Designation of personnel;



The grant of scholarship to its organic faculty members; and



4.2.6 Other policies that may be necessary for the effective and efficient school operation.

The college Executive Vice Presidents should judiciously discharge their respective functions for the efficient and effective administration and operation of the school;



The school should cancel the job order contracts of instructors who were hired as such but without teaching loads and thereafter execute another contract embodying therewith the true nature of works they actually performed;



The college should implement the school policy of giving the faculty members the maximum teaching load of 24 units;

Additional task/s that may be assigned to the instructor shall form part of their respective administrative duties and should be without additional cost to the government except those pertaining to RATA or Extraordinary and Miscellaneous Expenses (EME) attached to the particular position the employee is designated to pursuant to Section 13.c.7 of the 2017 ORAOHRA;

4.6 Job orders, not being employees of the college, should not be given the benefits that the regular employees are enjoying like scholarship grants, etc. except if the same is sanctioned by law;



Scholarship contract should be executed by the college and the grantees stating therein the obligations of the parties to contract, including the requirement for the rendition of return service after the completion of the study grant;

Job description for certain positions should be clearly defined and spelled out by the management to avoid confusion of duties and responsibilities;



The college should re-evaluate and re-assess the dire necessity of hiring consultants. If unnecessary, proper action shall be made by the management.



The procuring entity should consider the provisions of RA 9184 and its IRR      in contracting the services of consultants;



The school management should monitor the outputs and accomplishments of consultants in accordance with the provisions of the contract of services;


The Accountant should require the submission of outputs and accomplishments of consultants and evaluate if the same is in accordance with the provisions of the contract of services before causing the payment for their services; and



4.13 Excess staff of GADTC should be transferred to other offices like CSWD, OCA, CEO, GSO, etc. after due consideration of their qualifications. Consequently, cancel the existing contract of those affected service contractors and execute another agreement to harmonize with the service requirements of a particular office.

In view of the foregoing observations, we recommended the following to the Agency:
The LCE should create an Inventory Committee who will handle the conduct of inventory-taking;
The inventory committee should (a) strictly conduct actual physical inventory-taking at least annually, (b) prepare a Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) using the prescribed format which must be fully filled up; (c) includes all types of PPEs in their inventory; (d) properly place property identification card/property tag to  each item of PPE;
The General Services Officer should (a) prepare the Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) evidencing receipt by the person in custody of the property; (b) make a renewal of ARE every three years; and (c) maintain and update property cards of all properties; and
The management should (a) send the GSO, inventory committee and other employees concern to actual trainings and seminars on the keeping, maintenance and disposition of PPE for proper guidance in property management; (b) properly install strong internal control in safeguarding the government’s properties; and (c) immediately make an inventory of all unserviceable properties and within a reasonable time, cause its disposal.

